text: If I agreed that Shanghai was communist, I'd agree entirely.

Is there another cipher that performs reliable digital reduction? I'm nowhere close to being versed in all of them (but I don't know of one). Not even Numeric Qwerty does.

... AQ is perfectly reliable for digital reduction because the numerals retain their ordinary arithmetical values. It equally performs (the somewhat exotic) hexadecimal reduction for the same reason. In fact, it can be understood as performing alphanumeric (base-36) reduction.

... Having actually looked at the damn thing (the cyphers.news app) I see immediately that it's swarming with ciphers performing reliable decimal digital reduction. Synx and Numeric Qwerty are in fact exceptional for not doing so. My bad. ...
... I'm in fact quite confused by this.

... When you look at, for e.g., the English Ordinal values table, it doesn't include numerals at all, yet when any numeral sequence is inputted it competently outputs digital reduction results. Someone please explain.
To 'do' digital reduction is to sum a number sequence (oblivious to magnitude, i.e. place value).
... This is my most unreliable post ever, and everything beyond the first sentence is wrong.
You might need to iterate, but digital reduction is best understood as iterative, too. Result will necessarily be sound.
